==========================================
Real-Time Use Case of Helm in a Company
==========================================

Company Name : ABC Technologies

Application : Employee Management System

Environments

1. Development (Dev)
2. QA (Testing)
3. Production (Prod)

==========================================
Without Helm
==========================================

Suppose the application has the following Kubernetes resources.

deployment.yaml
service.yaml
configmap.yaml
secret.yaml
ingress.yaml
hpa.yaml
pvc.yaml
serviceaccount.yaml

Total = 8 YAML files

Now there are 3 environments.

Dev
QA
Prod

So,

Dev

deployment-dev.yaml
service-dev.yaml
configmap-dev.yaml
secret-dev.yaml
...

QA

deployment-qa.yaml
service-qa.yaml
configmap-qa.yaml
secret-qa.yaml
...

Production

deployment-prod.yaml
service-prod.yaml
configmap-prod.yaml
secret-prod.yaml
...

Total

8 YAML files × 3 environments

= 24 YAML files

Imagine the company has

20 Microservices

Now

24 × 20

= 480 YAML files

Maintaining these files is very difficult.

==========================================
Problems Without Helm
==========================================

1. Duplicate YAML files

2. Manual editing for every environment

3. High chance of mistakes

4. Difficult to maintain

5. Time-consuming deployments

6. Upgrading applications is difficult

7. Rollback requires restoring old YAML files

8. Every developer follows a different YAML structure

==========================================
Solution Using Helm
==========================================

Instead of creating separate YAML files,

Create ONE Helm Chart.

employee-chart/

Chart.yaml

values.yaml

templates/

deployment.yaml

service.yaml

configmap.yaml

secret.yaml

ingress.yaml

hpa.yaml

==========================================
Create Environment-Specific Values Files
==========================================

values-dev.yaml

values-qa.yaml

values-prod.yaml

Only the configuration changes.

The templates remain the same.

==========================================
Example
==========================================

Development

Image

employee:v1-dev

Replicas

1

Database

dev-db

------------------------------------------

QA

Image

employee:v1-qa

Replicas

2

Database

qa-db

------------------------------------------

Production

Image

employee:v1

Replicas

5

Database

prod-db

==========================================
Deploy to Development
==========================================

helm install employee ./employee-chart \
-f values-dev.yaml

==========================================
Deploy to QA
==========================================

helm install employee ./employee-chart \
-f values-qa.yaml

==========================================
Deploy to Production
==========================================

helm install employee ./employee-chart \
-f values-prod.yaml

Notice:

The chart is the same.

Only values.yaml changes.

==========================================
Developer Gives a New Version
==========================================

Current Version

employee:v1

Developer builds

employee:v2

Without Helm

Edit deployment.yaml

Change image

Apply YAML

Verify

Repeat for Dev

Repeat for QA

Repeat for Production

==========================================
With Helm
==========================================

Update image tag

image:
  repository: company/employee
  tag: v2

Upgrade

helm upgrade employee ./employee-chart \
-f values-prod.yaml

Done.

==========================================
Rollback
==========================================

Suppose Version 2 has a bug.

Without Helm

Find old deployment.yaml

Edit image tag

Deploy again

Time wasted.

==========================================

With Helm

Check history

helm history employee

Output

Revision 1

Revision 2

Revision 3

Rollback

helm rollback employee 2

Within seconds the application returns to the previous stable version.

